Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 13.7",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Idealized rotational-vibrational spectrum of a linear rigid rotor; for a \
single vibrational transition (in this case ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["n", "\[Prime]\[Prime]"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"0", " ", "to", " ", 
      SuperscriptBox["n", "\[Prime]"]}], "=", "1"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"35afac47-60e1-4b0a-82f7-301a601637d9"],
 ") there are transitions corresponding to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[CapitalDelta]", " ", "J"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1890f2cc-b557-4f2b-aa67-96055cc644fe"],
 ". As with the pure rotational spectra, changing the temperature alters the \
initial state population distribution, thereby altering the spectrum. Wolfram \
Demonstrations, Porscha McRobbie and Eitan Geva (March 2011), CC BY-NC-SA, \
https://demonstrations.wolfram.com/\
RotationalVibrationalSpectrumOfADiatomicMolecule/"
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
