   3.8159247404817953`*^9}, {3.8159945448318834`*^9, 3.815994713167585*^9}, {
   3.8160028965681047`*^9, 3.8160028965691357`*^9}, 3.9398953364641533`*^9, {
   3.9400904386486473`*^9, 
   3.940090438812069*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"586d34c2-9af5-476c-9140-\
b8542781de33"],

Cell["\<\
Beyond linear rigid rotors, the rotational-vibrational coupling is much more \
complicated. For symmetric top molecules, the observed distribution is \
typically classified by whether the change in the dipole moment for a given \
vibration is perpendicular or parallel to the axis of the unique moment of \
inertia. So-called parallel bands give a structure similar to that of a rigid \
rotor with P-, Q-, and R-branches, whereas the substructure of a \
perpendicular band is more complex. For asymmetric tops, the rotational \
substructure is even more complicated. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8160013594566584`*^9, 3.816001364554344*^9}, {
  3.8160013953338566`*^9, 3.816001451710765*^9}, {3.816001618926225*^9, 
  3.8160016288261857`*^9}, {3.816001735860497*^9, 3.8160018160439396`*^9}, {
  3.8160074738792562`*^9, 
  3.816007476475569*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"43dc4cdd-af6c-462e-9fae-\
64c1d2cfdcd6"],

Cell["\<\
Note that all of the discussion of rotational structure thus far assumes a \
relatively small molecule in the gas phase. In solution or solid phase, the \
rotations will be hindered, thereby broadening the rotational distribution \
and making any substructure unresolvable. In addition, the rotational \
constants of larger molecules are typically so small that the laser linewidth \
is too broad to resolve any rotational structure, even for gas-phase samples.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.816001819071681*^9, 3.81600190067915*^9}, {
  3.816002791379793*^9, 
  3.8160028887331705`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e6e78cd9-3c76-4c4b-965b-\
a17955200e3d"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Electronic Spectra", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8160031069396963`*^9, 
  3.816003109381568*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4f473c70-e472-46f5-b9b0-\
409f01bc3726"],

Cell["\<\
As one can surmise from Figure 13.1, electronic transitions are always \
accompanied by vibrational and rotational transitions. Because the energy \
spacing of the rotational states is quite small relative to the electronic \
state spacing, this substructure is typically not resolved in spectroscopic \
experiments, and we focus here on the vibrational-electronic, or vibronic, \
transitions. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8160039429127083`*^9, 3.8160042264887805`*^9}, {
   3.8160043315078006`*^9, 3.816004593233942*^9}, 
   3.939895337207796*^9},ExpressionUUID->"6e49a16a-6d30-43af-b06e-\
9a91e634615f"],

