   3.815469253967925*^9}, {3.815469801580475*^9, 3.8154698049489393`*^9}, {
   3.8154704295945253`*^9, 3.8154705377746935`*^9}, {3.815470675960216*^9, 
   3.815470685687868*^9}, {3.8154771921536026`*^9, 3.8154772311980553`*^9}, {
   3.815477347847094*^9, 3.815477378878831*^9}, {3.8154781257511315`*^9, 
   3.815478223009077*^9}, {3.8154786358518734`*^9, 3.8154786389651012`*^9}, {
   3.8154786960548897`*^9, 3.8154786979311686`*^9}, {3.815478752042659*^9, 
   3.8154787864116263`*^9}, {3.815478846570588*^9, 3.815478870033407*^9}, {
   3.8154793192990932`*^9, 3.8154793232406645`*^9}, {3.8154794670370035`*^9, 
   3.8154794764432354`*^9}, {3.8154827001319475`*^9, 
   3.8154827649959607`*^9}, {3.815754454341432*^9, 3.815754455861507*^9}, {
   3.815755043689207*^9, 3.81575504640403*^9}, 3.8157559076864185`*^9, 
   3.8157559845101175`*^9, {3.8157561148226886`*^9, 3.8157561432247086`*^9}, {
   3.815756206037531*^9, 3.8157562153683667`*^9}, {3.8157562600399704`*^9, 
   3.815756261111499*^9}, {3.815756300371641*^9, 3.815756304417721*^9}, {
   3.8158405029989915`*^9, 3.815840503548552*^9}, {3.8158408061213017`*^9, 
   3.815840830215969*^9}, {3.8158411679934397`*^9, 3.815841189669236*^9}, {
   3.815842438284893*^9, 3.815842485006773*^9}, {3.8158425874927773`*^9, 
   3.8158426251480494`*^9}, {3.8158426578419857`*^9, 3.815842704558471*^9}, 
   3.8158451926335983`*^9, {3.8158452428271637`*^9, 3.815845247949366*^9}, 
   3.81584529401821*^9, {3.8158453505599775`*^9, 3.8158453827011056`*^9}, {
   3.8158456187602577`*^9, 3.815845654351219*^9}, {3.8158456902217584`*^9, 
   3.8158457357536354`*^9}, 3.8158466451818304`*^9, {3.816004615921261*^9, 
   3.8160046324482756`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"781a410a-13b1-47bf-8e11-\
c31de6fdfa34"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the case of a diatomic molecule, the greater the overlap between the \
ground-state and excited-state eigenfunctions as a function of the \
internuclear distance ",
 StyleBox["R",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", the greater the probability of the transition, and the higher the \
intensity of the associated spectral line in the absorption spectrum. As the \
difference between the equilibrium internuclear distance of the ground and \
excited states increases, the probability of transition to a higher-energy \
vibrational state of the excited state also increases."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8160047450961204`*^9, 
  3.81600495115561*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"36306a48-b3a1-4051-8ac9-\
4455afc9113b"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Group Theory", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8161598589847293`*^9, 
  3.8161598612509127`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"176b71fc-9e80-4c51-b807-\
433a60340fc9"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162535594294453`*^9, 
  3.8162535605534925`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7f9501db-c785-4ad8-b4cf-\
d782a675ff6d"],

Cell["\<\
Group theory was originally developed as a mathematical tool, but for \
chemists, it has found widespread applications in the analysis of molecular \
properties and structure. Some applications of group theory include reduction \
of complexity in Fock matrices, labeling of molecular orbitals, prediction of \
allowed electronic transitions, and prediction of molecular vibrations. We \
will focus here on the application of group theory to molecular vibrations.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162535638374047`*^9, 
  3.816253675372882*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"648c262d-f2f5-4b14-80f4-\
1ce5419718ff"],

Cell["\<\
We will discuss symmetry operations, specific movements of the atoms about \
planes or axes of symmetry that leave the structure unchanged, and we will \
see that all of the symmetry operations for a molecule define its point \
group. We will then introduce character tables and how they give us \
information on molecular vibrations.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.816253712347951*^9, 
  3.8162538041085052`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5b73f540-a2ba-45cc-9b1c-\
34e7ed863709"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Symmetry Operations and Elements", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.816159868071905*^9, 3.8161598714589977`*^9}, {
  3.8162538326938095`*^9, 
  3.816253834043955*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ebc62ba2-ef5e-4a66-b6c2-\
704b44829969"],

Cell["\<\
As discussed above, a symmetry operation is a movement of the atoms in a \
molecule that leaves the initial structure unchanged. For each symmetry \
operation, there is an associated symmetry element, an axis, plane, or point \
that is a reference for applying the operation. There are five classes of \
symmetry operations for molecules that we will reference.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162538372698216`*^9, 3.816253986599043*^9}, {
  3.816254031330969*^9, 3.8162540318218656`*^9}, {3.816254118378332*^9, 
  3.81625413622736*^9}, {3.8162549136050653`*^9, 3.81625491445891*^9}, {
  3.8162550690870123`*^9, 
  3.8162550761255755`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2cd0c07e-ae5b-40f2-8167-\
5ba66012a93d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "Identity Operation: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   OverscriptBox["E", "^"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1d5a1a45-4456-40a0-a9dd-3196eb9deace"]
}], "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.816253991053035*^9, 3.8162540030112953`*^9}, {
   3.816254123842614*^9, 3.816254125581726*^9}, {3.8162549052422514`*^9, 
   3.816254905827611*^9}, {3.8162550640416813`*^9, 3.8162550649216785`*^9}, {
   3.8162551312371273`*^9, 3.816255141901766*^9}, 
   3.8162565452732396`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"33c1574f-b6ff-41a4-9da8-\
8ff383670e2d"],

Cell["\<\
In the identity operation, we don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t do anything to the \
molecule. There is no associated axis, plane, or point of symmetry. All \
molecules have at least this identity element, and many molecules have only \
this element, for example carbamic acid (Figure 13.9)\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162540062712617`*^9, 3.8162540068218884`*^9}, {
   3.816254037786107*^9, 3.8162541072516537`*^9}, {3.8162541396455507`*^9, 
   3.8162542758262053`*^9}, {3.8162543689237356`*^9, 
   3.8162543707545323`*^9}, {3.8162546703405447`*^9, 3.8162546862316275`*^9}, 
   3.939895339979082*^9, {3.940090456910597*^9, 
   3.940090457432823*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c516be72-c6b0-4869-b7ba-\
6bd595e29f31"],

