Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Molecular Point Groups", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162595217896233`*^9, 
  3.81625953430107*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"80bf10e7-e5bd-454f-b6ff-\
850bb91a25b8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Within group theory, a ",
 StyleBox["group",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " has a very specific definition, and the elements of a group must obey \
certain rules. We won\[CloseCurlyQuote]t go through these definitions and \
rules in this course. Instead, we skip ahead and state that we can classify \
molecules based upon the symmetry elements that they possess. We call the set \
of all symmetry elements associated with a molecule the molecular point \
group. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.81625958752503*^9, 3.816259641451088*^9}, {
  3.8162596735170574`*^9, 3.816259833693735*^9}, {3.8162598794044085`*^9, 
  3.816259915686349*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6eefd059-22fb-4b91-bbed-\
ed7ebbd15e0e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "To identify the point group associated with a given molecular structure, it \
is easiest to follow a flow chart such as the one shown in Figure 13.14. \
These charts assist in identifying the symmetry elements of a molecule and \
assembling them to assign the point group. You can work through many examples \
using this chart at ",
 ButtonBox["https://symotter.org/challenge",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://symotter.org/challenge"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://symotter.org/challenge"],
 "."
