   3.8160103359781947`*^9}, {3.8162547010176077`*^9, 
   3.8162547601720486`*^9}, {3.816256470388248*^9, 3.8162564938155575`*^9}, {
   3.8162573507149153`*^9, 3.8162574489332633`*^9}, {3.8162575055320253`*^9, 
   3.816257507198513*^9}, {3.8162581563329887`*^9, 3.8162581865642414`*^9}, {
   3.8162592800669956`*^9, 3.8162593063362246`*^9}, {3.8162601211201*^9, 
   3.816260169699456*^9}, {3.816269019310587*^9, 3.8162690739520535`*^9}, 
   3.9398953534494286`*^9, {3.94009052922007*^9, 
   3.9400905298371944`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b61a10e6-a03e-46f8-921c-\
136c91e72edb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Water belongs to the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox[
   SubscriptBox["C", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["2",
      FontSlant->"Plain"], "v"}]],
   FontSlant->"Italic"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9fddaf6d-84c9-4133-88cd-b73780433c1f"],
 " point group, and we can then see how each symmetry operation impacts the \
symmetric stretch vibration ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 3.816269158697982*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"6d98b248-7929-4a88-abdf-902519ee756a"],
 ","
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.816269001192651*^9, {3.816269164103766*^9, 
   3.8162691702916265`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"78f807ba-5e69-4959-87d3-\
d45b07cb5bc6"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "=", 
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["C",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "2"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "=", 
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "^"], 
    StyleBox["v",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "=", 
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "^"], 
    StyleBox["v",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Prime]"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}], "=", 
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "s"]}]}], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 
  3.8162692202978635`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"086eac4d-c020-4fde-97c3-\
fbbcb6feba18"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where by convention the molecule is situated in the ",
 StyleBox["yz",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " plane. In matrix form, we could represent these transformations as {1, 1, \
1, 1}, and we would then say that the symmetric stretch vibration belongs to \
the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["A", "1"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "3e0db59c-052c-43af-96e0-6000d9d1eaf2"],
 " irreducible representation. We can apply the same procedure to the \
asymmetric stretch vibration ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 3.8162692202978635`*^9}, {
   3.816269421872278*^9, 3.8162694311990795`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->
  "f6db9ab9-d8a8-40f6-8450-e7317937085d"],
 ","
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162692744949274`*^9, 3.816269291260784*^9}, {
  3.816269355398653*^9, 
  3.8162694345818443`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"abafd447-8ee9-4b4a-90b9-\
1c66ec68e516"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}], "=", 
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["C",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "2"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{"-", 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "^"], 
    StyleBox["v",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{"-", 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "^"], 
    StyleBox["v",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Prime]"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}], "=", 
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]}]}], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 3.8162692202978635`*^9}, {
   3.816269421872278*^9, 3.8162694539690113`*^9}, 3.816269485234948*^9, {
   3.8163653328304315`*^9, 3.816365335357482*^9}, 
   3.9405208793177032`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"1f913938-0f14-486c-8964-\
2fa378f9cdde"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "we see that the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["C",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "^"], "2"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 3.8162692202978635`*^9}, {
    3.816269421872278*^9, 3.8162694539690113`*^9}, 3.816269485234948*^9, {
    3.8163653328304315`*^9, 3.816365335357482*^9}, 3.9405208793177032`*^9},
  ExpressionUUID->"38bfcbe4-9cc5-fb44-8d74-24b89eeec009"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   OverscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "^"], 
   StyleBox["v",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 3.8162692202978635`*^9}, {
    3.816269421872278*^9, 3.8162694539690113`*^9}, 3.816269485234948*^9},
  ExpressionUUID->"f4b397d3-7c16-4a4a-b5a6-a7ced3a0c045"],
 " operations change the direction of the vibration of the two hydrogen \
atoms, so multiplication by \[Minus]1 is required to maintain the equality. \
The matrix representation is then {1, \[Minus]1, \[Minus]1, 1}, and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox["\[Nu]", "as"]],
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162691334827547`*^9, 3.8162692202978635`*^9}, {
    3.816269421872278*^9, 3.8162694539690113`*^9}, 3.816269485234948*^9},
  ExpressionUUID->"6c7b7278-d02b-439d-9c58-88d88d841835"],
 " therefore belongs to the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "99f968d8-ab9f-4bc5-8541-cb41e49f88b3"],
 " irreducible representation."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162694984465113`*^9, 3.8162696105698643`*^9}, {
  3.816365337703758*^9, 3.81636534611648*^9}, {3.9405208880203876`*^9, 
  3.9405209070455704`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"67f6fee2-4def-42e5-a20d-\
4e6f0a5a3063"],

Cell["\<\
One can go even further and determine the number of molecular vibrations \
belonging to each irreducible representation (without knowing the type of \
vibration beforehand), but we won\[CloseCurlyQuote]t cover this derivation. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8162696191802373`*^9, 
  3.8162696849104233`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c1fdad84-8210-4ead-ad90-\
1f5afbbd93e2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Most computational chemistry programs will provide the irreducible \
representation to which a vibration belongs. Below is some output from the \
Gaussian program for a molecule belonging to the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["C", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6eaa3757-945e-4369-bc94-83eff36045c8"],
 " point group:"
}], "Text",
